<v LastAir>Alright, so picture this. Nineteen seventy-eight, Slamecka and Graf run these studies. Here's what sticks with me: when organics try to generate an answer, even if they're swinging and missing, they end up remembering the right answer way better than if it was just handed to them. That's the generation effect. (pause) Fast forward to two thousand seven, a meta-analysis combs through eighty-six studies. Effect size of zero point four, which is a big deal in psychology. But wait, it gets wilder: when you wait more than a day, that effect jumps to zero point six four. The brain isn't just storing info; it gets built by reaching for what's not there yet. It's fascinating.</v>

